core::option::Option::<T>::unwrap.doc:
Returns the contained [`Some`] value, consuming the `self` value.

 Because this function may panic, its use is generally discouraged.
 Panics are meant for unrecoverable errors, and
 [may abort the entire program][panic-abort].

 Instead, prefer to use pattern matching and handle the [`None`]
 case explicitly, or call [`unwrap_or`], [`unwrap_or_else`], or
 [`unwrap_or_default`]. In functions returning `Option`, you can use
 [the `?` (try) operator][try-option].

 [panic-abort]: https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/ch09-01-unrecoverable-errors-with-panic.html
 [try-option]: https://doc.rust-lang.org/book/ch09-02-recoverable-errors-with-result.html#where-the--operator-can-be-used
 [`unwrap_or`]: Option::unwrap_or
 [`unwrap_or_else`]: Option::unwrap_or_else
 [`unwrap_or_default`]: Option::unwrap_or_default

 # Panics

 Panics if the self value equals [`None`].

 # Examples

 ```
 let x = Some("air");
 assert_eq!(x.unwrap(), "air");
 ```

 ```should_panic
 let x: Option<&str> = None;
 assert_eq!(x.unwrap(), "air"); // fails
 ```

collections::btree::node::NodeRef::<coll.doc:
Mutably borrows the owned root node. Unlike `reborrow_mut`, this is safe
 because the return value cannot be used to destroy the root, and there
 cannot be other references to the tree.

core::panicking::panic.doc: The underlying implementation of core's `panic!` macro when no formatting is used.

collections::btree::node::NodeRef::<coll.doc:
Adds a key-value pair to the end of the node, and returns
 the mutable reference of the inserted value.

collections::btree::node::Handle::<colle.doc:
Finds the node pointed to by this edge.

 The method name assumes you picture trees with the root node on top.

 `edge.descend().ascend().unwrap()` and `node.ascend().unwrap().descend()` should
 both, upon success, do nothing.

collections::btree::node::NodeRef::<coll.doc:
Adds a new internal node with a single edge pointing to the previous root node,
 make that new node the root node, and return it. This increases the height by 1
 and is the opposite of `pop_internal_level`.

Adds a key-value pair, and an edge to go to the right of that pair,
 to the end of the node.
